              "4.1 Logical correctness (15)": "6/15 - Main command dispatch mostly matches required commands (X,C,+,*,%,@,neg,D,digits). PUSH/POP follow a descending stack idea, but several operations are logically wrong: XOR routine clobbers R6 (stack pointer) as a temp and also uses R5 (status) as a temp, so stack/state are corrupted. Display pops but does not correctly re-push (just does ADD R6,#-1 without storing the value back). Multiply sign handling is incorrect (only tracks multiplier sign; product sign should depend on both operands). Modulo loop appears incorrect (adds divisor instead of subtracting, and remainder/sign logic is inconsistent). Restore helpers only adjust R6, but do not restore popped values; they also assume simple pointer rewinds are safe, which is not generally correct when intervening writes/reads occurred.",
              "4.2 Assembleability (10)": "2/10 - As submitted, it would not assemble cleanly: the file is truncated (e.g., \"Underfl\"), so multiple labels/data (StackBase/StackMax/ASCIIBUFF/LookUp tables/Mask constants/etc.) are missing. There are also invalid immediate forms like \"ADD R3,R0,xFFF6\" and \"ADD R3,R0,xFFEA\" (ADD immediate must be 5-bit signed). The XOR loop uses BRn/BRzp in a way that likely forms an infinite loop. Even ignoring truncation, several referenced labels/constants (Mask16, Mask1, Mask2, NewlineChar, MaxDigits, NegASCIIOffset, LookUp10/100, ASCIIoffset, Pos100/Neg100, Neg10, ASCIIplus/minus, Neg999/Pos999, Save/Save1, StackBase/StackMax, ASCIIBUFF) are not shown/defined here.",
              "4.3 Edge case handling (10)": "3/10 - RangeCheck intent is correct, but the comparisons appear wrong as written: using Pos999 and adding to R0 does not implement an upper-bound check unless Pos999 is actually -999; constant naming suggests a bug risk. On range error, stack restoration is attempted by rewinding R6, but because POP advanced R6, rewinding without re-storing operands relies on old memory still containing operands and no other clobbering—fragile but sometimes workable; however XOR clobbers R6 so this breaks. Underflow/overflow messages exist, but PUSH overflow check is suspicious (tests BRz on computed difference rather than proper boundary condition) and POP underflow check depends on exact initial SP convention. ASCIItoBinary only supports up to 3 digits and no sign; PushValue also uses invalid immediates for newline/CR detection. BinarytoASCII always prints sign plus 3 digits but does not null-terminate ASCIIBUFF, so PUTS will run past buffer unless ASCIIBUFF is pre-zeroed/terminated elsewhere.",
